                    <occupation type="political">daǧǧāzmač</occupation>
                    <floruit notBefore="1597" notAfter="1605">He was a minor feudal lord from a locality
                        <placeName ref="LOC3440Gesse"/> in the district of <placeName ref="LOC4544Manz"/> of the province of 
                        <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/>. As his life-story exemplifies, the struggle for power that followed the death 
                        of King <persName ref="PRS8550sardaDe"/> could give a war lord vast opportunities for booty and promotion, 
                        but for premature death as well. In <date>1602</date>, with 800 of his warriors, 
                        he came to one of the pretenders to the throne, the future <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos">
                            <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>Susǝnyos</persName>. 
                        However, <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos">
                                <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>Susǝnyos</persName> suspected perfidy, arrested him and looted his native 
                        <placeName ref="LOC4544Manz"/>. Faris fled but after the death of 
                        <persName ref="PRS10513Zadenge"/> in <date>1604</date>, he came to <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos"/>
                        again and concluded an alliance with him. However, after <date>1605</date>, he decided to go over 
                        <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos"/>'s rival <persName ref="PRS10198Yaeqob"> 
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName> Yāʿqob</persName>,
                        but was arrested again and once more fled to his native
                        <placeName ref="LOC4544Manz"/>. When <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos"/> came there in 
                        December <date>1605</date>, Faris sought refuge on an amba called 
                        <placeName ref="LOC2591Dayar"/> and was killed during its siege.
                    </floruit>
                    <death when="1605"/>
